Here's the registration pattern:

```csharp
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // One HttpClient + data service for the whole app
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<HttpClient>();
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // New ViewModel instance per request (fresh state each navigation)
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // New page instance per request (pairs with its ViewModel)
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why these lifetimes:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `HttpClient` | **Singleton** | Reusing one instance avoids socket exhaustion. |
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Stateless API wrapper — sharing it saves memory and lets you cache if needed. |
| ViewModels | **Transient** | Each navigation should get fresh state (selected item, form fields, etc.). |
| Pages | **Transient** | Pairs 1:1 with their ViewModel; a new page avoids stale UI from a previous visit. |

**Inject via constructor** — MAUI's DI handles the rest:

```csharp
public partial class MainPage : ContentPage
{
    public MainPage(MainViewModel vm)
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        BindingContext = vm;
    }
}
```

> **Tip:** If you later need per-request scoping (e.g., a unit-of-work database context), use `AddScoped` — but MAUI doesn't create scopes automatically, so `Transient` vs `Scoped` behaves the same unless you manage scopes yourself.
